description:
FOLLOW-UP from Epic E PR #130 review. json_union.py currently reproduces jq's exact output bytes (the _jq_sort_key total-order ranks, the sorted-skeleton-vs-insertion-order passthrough dance, the empty-object [] | add == null quirk, and number-lexeme handling) solely to pass the transitional golden-master parity diff (design doc: Golden-master is 'the parity safety net for the side-by-side window only' and retires at parity-gate + 14 days; 'divergence is welcome — particularly when the Python fixes latent install.sh bugs').

PROPOSAL — replace with a semantic deep-merge (~1/3 the code, dependency-free, more correct):
- recursive dict merge, existing-wins on scalar/type conflict (unchanged);
- arrays: concatenate + dedupe by value, preserve first-seen order -> ELIMINATES _jq_sort_key entirely (the total-order ranks exist only to sort mixed-type arrays jq-style);
- output via json.dumps(indent=2, sort_keys=True) -> drops the skeleton/passthrough subtlety and largely dissolves the number-lexeme + int-overflow edge cases we chased in review;
- no empty-object null quirk (a jq wart we currently reproduce for byte-parity).

ENABLING PREREQUISITE (decide at H.1 design time): the golden-master harness (tests/golden_master/_runner.py, story H.1) must JSON-NORMALIZE .json files (parse both sides, compare semantically) before its recursive diff — otherwise the settings-merge scenario fails on a byte diff. Alternatively this waits until golden-master retirement (H.5). Build H.1 with this in mind.

TEST CHURN: the ~34 jq-parity tests in test_json_union.py rewrite to pin semantic behavior instead of jq bytes.

OPTIONAL: evaluate mergedeep/deepmerge (PyPI) vs hand-rolled; lean hand-rolled to keep deps minimal (pip-audit gate).
